replies.text:
@ThinkingandTinkering glad to lend helping hands er, conversations lol. 
I gotta say, your battery work is spectacular. What brought me to your channel initially. And how well you can read through and explain scientific papers is also commendable.
I look forward to more.

@ThinkingandTinkering Hiya Robert, just thinking out loud, they have the insulation on the inside not sure if they have decreased the diameter of the tube? If you put tubes inside for the air this will further decrease the diameter of the tube potentially affecting the efficiency? 
Also feeding pipe in through the burn chamber with a 90-degree bend at the end (the gases aren't going to be preheated as much but this is an option.
Just a thought about my first suggestion, if the tubes entered at an angle would this create a vortex and increase performance?

@ThinkingandTinkering Hi Robert. I heartily agree with the KISS principles in design. That said, there is a trade-off of efficiency for simplicity. With the liberty stove design, or any other for that matter, would you investigate or comment regarding the use of preheated intake air for a more complete/efficient combustion? For example, using a small (4 blade, 4 inch) heat-driven fan, with minimal +pressure and moving ±5 CFM, there may be a potential benefit to these heater systems. The said unit would clamp on to an existing heater fixture frame, tube, etc. and provided as an add-on for the manufacturer or an aftermarket accessory. Thanks again for your inquisitive and practical videos. 
Another thought regarding the heater tank/chamber would be to incorporate vertical metal baffle plates with many perforations to act as a passive heat sink or storage. Their special arrangements would capture the heat but not be overly restrictive to the gas flow. 

I should stop now. Good luck.

@ThinkingandTinkering Variant add on - 'quadrant' shaped drums filled with sand that  bolt to put side of burn drum.

Other thing often missing from rocket stoves is higher capacity fuel feed so that it can be left longer between refueling - pellet hopper??

Also when I was thinking about rocket stoves my 'design' got (on paper) as far as something like the liberator but half the height but the rear drum had fresh air pipes coming in from the base and running up to near the 'lid' to bring heated fresh air into the drum to give more efficient secondary burn.
